# Git Workflow

> Small, focused commits. Clear messages. One issue per branch, one branch per PR.

## Branch-Based Workflow

`origin` is the canonical repo. Work on short-lived feature branches, never
directly on `main`. Open a pull request from the feature branch into `main`.

## Branch Naming

Use kebab-case. Include the issue number when applicable.

| Type | Format | Example |
|------|--------|---------|
| Feature | `feature/description` | `feature/12-task-crud-api` |
| Bug fix | `fix/description` | `fix/13-priority-filter-datatype` |
| Chore | `chore/description` | `chore/ci-lint-workflow` |
| Docs | `docs/description` | `docs/orm-optimization-notes` |

## Commit Messages - Conventional Commits

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`.

```bash
# Good
git commit -m "feat(api): add project summary action with single annotated query"
git commit -m "fix(filters): use ChoiceFilter for priority to avoid DataError"

# Bad
git commit -m "wip"
git commit -m "updates"
```

Do not use an em dash in commit messages, branch names, PR titles, or PR
descriptions. Use a regular hyphen or rephrase.

## Never Rebase Shared Branches

Always merge. Do not `git rebase` or `git pull --rebase` on branches others may
share. If a push is rejected because the remote is ahead, `git pull --no-rebase`
then push.

## PRs

- Link the issue the PR closes (`Closes #N`).
- Keep the PR scoped to a single logical change.
- CI (lint + type-check + tests) must be green before merge.
- Prefer squash-and-merge into `main` to keep history clean.
